Purpose.--The purpose of this report is to summarize the experience of the Harvard Refugee interview Project’, indicating proce- dures of value for interviewing Russians under voluntary conditions. This report is essentially a consensus of impressions, suggestions, and information gathered: (1) from discussions with the inter- viewing staff oi the Harvard Pro- ject and with several persons who in other capacities have inter- viewed Russians; and (2) from an analysis oi the interview records oi the project. The information from these sources was as- tonishingly consistent in spite of the diverse professional training represented. z. Definitions.--The term “Russians” has been used throughout the report to de- scribe the people interviewed by the Harvard Project. This has been done in part to avoid more correct but cumbersome phrases such as “former Soviet citizens.” in addition, the majority ot the respondents were actually Great Russians, and 93 percent of all respond- ents were Slavic (Great Russians, Ukrainians, and Byelorussians). Although some ferences among the Slavic groups are dis- cussed later, the generalizations about Rus- sians are essentially applicable, at least for interviewing purposes, to the other Slavic nationalities living in the USSR. In the dis- cussion on national differences within the Soviet Union, the term “Russians” denotes «Great Russians” in contradistinction to the national minorities in the USSR. Scope and limitations.--The people interviewed by members of the staff of the Harvard Project were either wartime dis- placed persons or members oi the Soviet occupation forces who had left the Soviet sec- tors of Germany and Austria after World War IL? The majority of these respondents were currently living in camps for displaced per- sons or were living independently within the German econorny, These respondents were paid for their time as an inducement to volun- teer to be interviewed. In addition to this group, a few persons living in military custody were interviewed.
